This may help
```js
const server = createServer(bot, {
  verifyToken: '__FILL_YOUR_VERIFY_TOKEN_HERE__'
});
```
https://bottender.js.org/docs/Guides-Server#options

```js
const allActions = {
  helloWorld: {
    method: 'sendMessage',
    args: ['*Hello world*', { parse_mode: 'Markdown' } ],
  },
  photo: {
    method: 'sendPhoto',
    args: ['https://i.imgur.com/SQltmALl.jpg', {
      reply_markup: {
        inline_keyboard: [
          [ 
            { 
              text: 'Google',
              url: 'https://www.google.com',
            },
          ],
        ],
      },
      parse_mode: 'Markdown',
      disable_web_page_preview: false,
    },
    ]
  }
};

bot.use(context => {
  context.doActions = async action => {
    await context[action.method](...action.args);
  };
});

bot.onEvent(async context => {
  await context.doActions(allActions.helloWorld);
  await context.doActions(allActions.photo);
});
```

How about this?

@chentsulin , here is an example , when using quick replies to get a user location on messenger , we can't send payload with it , so I had to set few data with setState , which i will remove in the next event call , by suggesting lifeTime option , a developer can gain time and few lines using bottender .

```javascript
context.setState(
{ 
	context : WEATHER,
	query : data.result.resolvedQuery,
	type : "location"
});
context.sendQuickReplies({ text: 'I need your location:' }, [{"content_type": "location"}]);
```
and then when the next event fires

```javascript
if(context.event.location)
{
	var coordinates = context.event.location.coordinates ;
	context.setState(
	{ 
		context : null,
		query : null,
		type : null
	});
}
```

as you can see I can't use ```resetState``` because I have other states which I need in few further events

It seems reasonable to me to keep state and reset it in this case.

You may receive location messages even when you are not asking:

```js
if (context.event.isLocation) {
  if (context.state.isAskingLocation) {
    const coordinates = context.event.location.coordinates;
    context.setState({
      isAskingLocation: false,
    });
  } else {
    // Should we do something else here?
  }
}
```

If some state should be grouped together, we can put them into an object:

```js
context.setState({
  xxx: {
    context : WEATHER,
    query : data.result.resolvedQuery,
    type : 'location',
  },
});
```

Then we can clean them up in one step:

```js
context.setState({
  xxx: null,
});
```
